"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921927","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-06-14","<p>The Office for Civil Society has been part of DCMS since the Machinery of Government change on 21<sup>st</sup> July 2016.</p><p> </p><p>The number of OCS staff on permanent contracts in each of the last two years is as follows:</p><ul><li>31 March 2017 - 64</li><li>31 March 2018 - 52</li></ul><p> </p><p>In addition to those on permanent contracts, as at 31 March 2018, 37 additional staff were employed on a combination of fixed term contracts, loan and secondments.</p><p> </p><p>DCMS does not hold records for before the Machinery of Government transfer.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2018-06-14T14:48:15.223Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921927/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921927/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921927/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-06-11","Office for Civil Society: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, how many permanent members of staff have been assigned to the Office for Civil Society in each year since it was established.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","152187"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921928","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-06-14","<p>The previous figure published by DWP was a preliminary estimate of the expected impact of implementing the judgment; we have since updated the analysis with a larger sample. The estimated impacts arising from the later sample were not as large as seen in the earlier, smaller sample. The Office for Budget Responsibility (OBR) are an independent body that provides scrutiny of departmental forecasts for fiscal events, including specific costing exercises such as this. OBR chose to publish the later, larger sample of the MH implementation costs, as this is likely to be more representative.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2018-06-14T15:17:04.703Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921928/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921928/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921928/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-06-11","Personal Independence Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to Table 8, page 21 of Equality Analysis PIP assessment criteria: Upper Tribunal judgments on daily living activity 3 and mobility activity 1, published by her Department in February 2017, and to paragraph 4.112, page 135, of Office for Budget Responsibility: Economic and fiscal outlook, published on March 2018, for what reason the estimate of the number of claimants affected by the judgment of RF v Secretary of Stat for Work and Pensions has been reduced from 336,500 to 165,000.","false","Biography information for Marsha De Cordova","Battersea","Marsha De Cordova","152297"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921929","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-06-19","<p>The changes to the methodology used by the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) in the development of guidance on highly specialised technologies do not affect the right enshrined in the NHS Constitution to NICE recommended drugs. National Health Service patients continue to have a right to drugs and treatments recommended in NICE technology appraisal and highly specialised technologies guidance provided their clinician considers it is appropriate treatment for them.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-06-19T16:56:28.073Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921929/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921929/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921929/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-06-11","Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, whether he has made an assessment of the compatibility with the NHS constitution of the introduction of a Quality-Adjusted Life-Year threshold for highly specialised technologies .","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","152180"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921930","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-06-14","<p>The Local Sustainability Fund supported around 260 small and medium size charities and social enterprises to strengthen their organisations and help secure the future of their services. Grant holders project’s came to an end in June 2017. The total spend was £18.7 million.</p><p> </p><p>An evaluation was published in January 2018, which found that 94% of recipients reported improvement in the ‘strength, sustainability and resilience’ of their organisation. Improvements were reported in a range of areas including governance and leadership, strategic thinking and planning, income diversification and confidence and self-belief.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2018-06-14T14:52:14.953Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921930/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921930/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921930/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-06-11","Third Sector: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, how much and what proportion of the Local Sustainability Fund has been spent.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","152188"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921931","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-06-19","<p>In April 2017, the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) amended its methodology for the evaluation of highly specialised technologies to introduce a weighted cost per Quality Adjusted Life Year (QALY). Under the new methodology, technologies that deliver very significant health benefits can be recommended for routine use up to £300,000 per QALY gained.</p><p> </p><p>NICE introduced the new methodology following a public consultation and took into account a report produced by its Decision Support Unit titled ‘Priorities for the NICE Highly Specialised Technologies Programme Review of Methods’ as well as modelling of the impact on topics that had previously been evaluated through the highly specialised technologies programme.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-06-19T16:57:16.64Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921931/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921931/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921931/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-06-11","Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what the evidential basis was which was used to inform the introduction of a £100,000 quality adjusted life year threshold into the highly specialised technology process.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","152181"
