"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921966","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-06-14","<p>DWP offer a Rapid Response Service (RRS). This is a redundancy service designed to give support and advice to employers and their employees when under threat of redundancy. It is co-ordinated nationally by the National Employer and Partnership Team (NEPT) and is managed by Jobcentre Plus. Each Jobcentre Plus district deploy resources according to the situation and the requirements of the workforce. This service is available to be deployed in Birkenhead should a mandatory consultation period end, and a decision is made by House of Fraser about the support it requires from Jobcentre Plus. The RRS is delivered in partnership with a range of national and local partners, including National Careers Service and local service providers.</p><p> </p><p>The range of support available from Jobcentre Plus and partners may include:</p><p> </p><ul><li>Information advice and guidance.</li><li>Connecting people to jobs in the labour market.</li><li>Help with job search including CV writing, interview skills, where to find jobs and<br> how to apply for them.</li><li>Help to identify transferable skills and skills gaps (linked to the local labour<br> market).</li><li>Training to update skills, learn new ones and gain industry recognised<br> certification that will improve employability.</li><li>Help to overcome barriers to attending training or securing a job or <br> self-employment such as child care costs, necessary tools, work clothes, travel<br> costs etc.</li><li>For large redundancies we may also provide on-site services to promote jobs or<br> to take benefit claims.</li><li>On-site presentations to those affected.</li><li>Jobs Fairs and Job Clubs where appropriate.</li></ul>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2018-06-14T15:06:00.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921966/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921966/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921966/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-06-11","House of Fraser: Birkenhead","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if she will allocate additional resources to Birkenhead Jobcentre Plus to support House of Fraser employees whose jobs will be lost as a result of that company's decision to close its store in Birkenhead.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","152055"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921967","Home Office","false","2018-06-22","<p>The Public Sector Equality Duty, enshrined within the Equality Act 2010, requires all public bodies, including local authorities, to have due regard to the need to eliminate discrimination and advance equality of opportunity in respect of all of the protected characteristics established by the 2010 Act. It is for each public body to demonstrate that they have fulfilled this duty and have considered the impact of their policies on each of the protected characteristics. Anyone with concerns that public bodies are not fulfilling this duty should, in the first instance, contact the relevant authority directly.</p><p>The Government is sympathetic to issues in relation to accessibility to licensed premises for disabled people and with ensuring businesses and service providers comply with the requirements in the 2010 Act. The Government has previously announced it will consult relevant organisations to better understand the extent of the problem. We will also work with the National Association of Licensing Enforcement Officers and representatives of the licensed trade to explore what practical measures can be taken to ensure significant improvements.</p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins","152247","2018-06-22T11:20:52.063Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921967/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921967/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921967/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-06-11","Licensed Premises","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps he is taking to ensure that local authorities comply with the provisions of the Equality Act 2010 to (a) eliminate discrimination and (b) advance equality of opportunity when considering restaurant, entertainment and alcohol licensing applications and re-applications.","false","Biography information for Alex Chalk","Cheltenham","Alex Chalk","152246"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921968","Home Office","false","2018-06-22","<p>The Public Sector Equality Duty, enshrined within the Equality Act 2010, requires all public bodies, including local authorities, to have due regard to the need to eliminate discrimination and advance equality of opportunity in respect of all of the protected characteristics established by the 2010 Act. It is for each public body to demonstrate that they have fulfilled this duty and have considered the impact of their policies on each of the protected characteristics. Anyone with concerns that public bodies are not fulfilling this duty should, in the first instance, contact the relevant authority directly.</p><p>The Government is sympathetic to issues in relation to accessibility to licensed premises for disabled people and with ensuring businesses and service providers comply with the requirements in the 2010 Act. The Government has previously announced it will consult relevant organisations to better understand the extent of the problem. We will also work with the National Association of Licensing Enforcement Officers and representatives of the licensed trade to explore what practical measures can be taken to ensure significant improvements.</p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins","152246","2018-06-22T11:20:52.123Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921968/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921968/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921968/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-06-11","Licensed Premises","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what powers are available to local authorities to (a) investigate and (b) record breaches of the Equality Act 2010 in relation to licensed premises.","false","Biography information for Alex Chalk","Cheltenham","Alex Chalk","152247"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921969","Home Office","false","2018-06-14","<p>Published data on performance against service standards for immigration applications made in the UK and from overseas, and the proportion of those cases classified as non-straightforward, can be found here: (<a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/migration-transparency-data#uk-visas-and-immigration" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/migration-transparency-data#uk-visas-and-immigration</a>)</p><p>To meet these service standards, case-working functions allocate workload in an appropriate manner and as such there are a number of different objectives and targets in place. These are dependent on the level of experience and seniority of individual caseworkers across the different UKVI case-working routes and also take into account any reasonable adjustments required in order to fulfil our statutory duties under the Equality Act 2010.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-06-14T14:35:55.45Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921969/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921969/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921969/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-06-11","Immigration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether his Department has set performance targets for immigration caseworkers on decisions.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","152142"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921970","Department for Education","false","2018-06-14","<p>The Department publishes information on the number of pupils and students enrolled in schools, further education and higher education in the annual ‘Education and training statistics for the UK: 2017’ statistical release: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/education-and-training-statistics-for-the-uk-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/education-and-training-statistics-for-the-uk-2017</a>.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2018-06-14T16:25:48.747Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921970/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921970/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921970/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-06-11","Pupil Numbers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what information his Department holds on how many children are currently enrolled in a formal education setting.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","152056"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921971","Treasury","false","2018-06-14","<p>The Advisory Assessment Panel in this appointment process consisted of Tom Scholar (Permanent Secretary - HM Treasury), Charles Roxburgh (2<sup>nd</sup> Permanent Secretary - HM Treasury), Diana ‘Dido’ Harding (Non-Executive Director – Bank of England) and Lynne Peacock (Non-Executive Director – Nationwide Building Society). Details of the panel were made publicly available online at gov.uk.</p>","Salisbury","John Glen",,"2018-06-14T15:26:36.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921971/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921971/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921971/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-06-11","Court of Directors","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will publish the membership of the committee that recommended the appointment of Bradley Fried to the position of Chair of the Court of the Bank of England.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","152057"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921972","Home Office","false","2018-06-14","<p>On 8 March we launched a 12 week public consultation on proposals for a landmark domestic abuse Bill and a supporting package of practical action to transform the response to domestic abuse. The consultation closed on 31 May. Over 3,200 responses to the consultation were received. The responses to the consultation are being considered and a draft Bill will be published later this session.</p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins",,"2018-06-14T16:24:25.683Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921972/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921972/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921972/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-06-11","Domestic Abuse","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the timetable is for his Department to respond to it's consultation on the draft Domestic Violence and Abuse Bill; and what the timetable is for further steps to be taken in relation to that Bill.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","152131"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921973","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-06-18","<p>This information is not collected in the format requested.</p><p> </p><p>The Five Year Forward View Dashboard tracks expenditure for mental health at a national, regional and clinical commissioning group level and is available at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.england.nhs.uk/publication/mental-health-five-year-forward-view-dashboard" target="_blank">https://www.england.nhs.uk/publication/mental-health-five-year-forward-view-dashboard</a></p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2018-06-18T14:24:29.103Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921973/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921973/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921973/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-06-11","Mental Health Services: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care,  what estimate he has made of the cost of NHS mental health treatment for children aged (a) 0 up to 4 years, (b) 4 up to 11 years and (c) 11 to 16 years in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mr William Wragg","Hazel Grove","Mr William Wragg","152206"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921974","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-06-19","<p>The requested information is not centrally held.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2018-06-19T13:48:09.37Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921974/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921974/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921974/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-06-11","Accident and Emergency Departments: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what estimate he has made of the cost to the public purse of children admitted to A&E for accidents aged (a) 0 up to 4 years, (b) 4 up to 11 years and (c) 11 to 16 years of age in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mr William Wragg","Hazel Grove","Mr William Wragg","152207"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921975","Department for Education","false","2018-06-19","<p>Funding for alternative provision (AP) comes from the dedicated schools grant (DSG). Local authorities provide place funding of £10,000 for each AP place in a pupil referral unit or AP academy from their high needs budget within the DSG.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, top up funding for costs in excess of the £10,000 place funding may be required depending on the needs of the individual pupil. Where the local authority is responsible for a pupil in AP, the top up funding is paid from the local authority’s high needs budget. Where a school is responsible, the top up funding is paid from the school’s delegated budget share. Local authorities can also spend their DSG on other AP services.</p><p> </p><p>The following table shows how much local authorities have reported that they have spent on AP in the last three years. Comparable data for 2013-14 and 2017-18, data on how much schools have spent on AP, and data held by age or need are not available. The figures below reflect the amount local authorities have chosen to spend on AP specifically, from their high needs budgets. Overall high needs funding has increased from £5 billion in 2013-14 to a record high of £6 billion this year, giving every local authority a cash increase in funding.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Financial Year</p></td><td><p>AP Expenditure</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>£627,847,551</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>£616,523,970</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016-17</p></td><td><p>£648,593,976</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2018-06-19T15:52:19.8Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921975/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921975/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921975/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-06-11","Pupils: Behaviour Disorders","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education,what estimate he has made of the cost to the public purse of alternative provision for children with behavioural conditions aged (a) 0 up to 4 years (b) 4 up to 11 years and (c) 11 to 16 years in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mr William Wragg","Hazel Grove","Mr William Wragg","152208"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921976","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-06-19","<p>The Government is committed to ensuring that victims of crime get the support they need to cope with and, as far as possible, recover from the effects of crime.</p><p> </p><p>Neither MoJ or NHS England hold information on the breakdown of funding allocations to victims based on age.</p><p> </p><p>Under the 2016-2020 Violence Against Women and Girls strategy, the Government made a commitment to maintain funding for sexual violence support services at 2016/17 levels for the remainder of the spending review period. We continue to meet this commitment.</p><p> </p><p>Overall, MoJ is spending around £96m this year to fund support services for victims of crime. Around £68m of this has been allocated to Police and Crime Commissioners to locally commission or provide support services for victims of crime, including victims of sexual violence and child sexual abuse.</p><p> </p><p>In 2018/19 we have allocated just over £8m in funding for services supporting victims of sexual violence, including support for victims of child sexual abuse.</p><p> </p><p>Young child victims of abuse are generally supported by specialist NHS services. NHS England and the Home Office also have commissioning responsibilities for services to support child victims of abuse. NHS England gave uplifted investment from £9m in 2013 to £31m this year to commission an all age service with PCCs. The Home Office are funding the £7.2m Child House model in London.</p>","Charnwood","Edward Argar",,"2018-06-19T15:48:06.8Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921976/answer","Biography information for Edward Argar","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921976/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921976/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-06-11","Offences against Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how much funding his Department has allocated to support child victims of abuse for children aged (a) 0 to 4 years, (b) 4 to 11 years and (c) 11 to 16 years in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mr William Wragg","Hazel Grove","Mr William Wragg","152209"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921977","Department for Education","false","2018-06-14","<p>The department is in constant engagement with its Welsh counterparts.</p><p>A school’s governing body (or academy trust, in the case of academies) is responsible for making decisions about school uniform, including the PE kit.</p><p>Local authorities have discretionary powers to provide grants to assist parents with the cost of school uniform in cases of financial hardship and academies are free to do similar. Individual schools may wish to consider running schemes to provide assistance with the cost of uniform.</p><p>The department’s guidance on school uniform is clear that schools should give high priority to cost considerations. The guidance is available at: <a href="http://www.gov.uk/government/publications/school-uniform" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/publications/school-uniform</a>.</p><p>Decisions on uniform for optional extra-curricular activities are the responsibility of the relevant organising body. The Ministry of Defence provides uniform for those participating in the Cadet Expansion Programme.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi","152283","2018-06-14T16:50:54.527Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921977/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921977/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921977/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-06-11","Schools: Uniforms","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what financial support his Department provides to low-income families in England in relation to the cost of (a) school uniforms, (b) sports kits and (c) uniforms for (i) cadets, (ii) scouts and guides and (iii) out of school sports teams.","false","Biography information for Layla Moran","Oxford West and Abingdon","Layla Moran","152282"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921978","Department for Education","false","2018-06-14","<p>The department is in constant engagement with its Welsh counterparts.</p><p>A school’s governing body (or academy trust, in the case of academies) is responsible for making decisions about school uniform, including the PE kit.</p><p>Local authorities have discretionary powers to provide grants to assist parents with the cost of school uniform in cases of financial hardship and academies are free to do similar. Individual schools may wish to consider running schemes to provide assistance with the cost of uniform.</p><p>The department’s guidance on school uniform is clear that schools should give high priority to cost considerations. The guidance is available at: <a href="http://www.gov.uk/government/publications/school-uniform" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/publications/school-uniform</a>.</p><p>Decisions on uniform for optional extra-curricular activities are the responsibility of the relevant organising body. The Ministry of Defence provides uniform for those participating in the Cadet Expansion Programme.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi","152282","2018-06-14T16:50:54.59Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921978/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921978/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921978/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-06-11","Schools: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if he will hold discussions with his Welsh counterpart on the potential merits of providing funding to cover the cost of (a) school uniforms (b) sports kits and (c) uniforms for (i) cadets, (ii) scouts and guides and (iii) out of school sports teams for low income households.","false","Biography information for Layla Moran","Oxford West and Abingdon","Layla Moran","152283"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921979","Home Office","false","2018-06-19","<p>On 8 March we launched a 12 week public consultation on proposals for a landmark domestic abuse Bill and a supporting package of practical action to transform the response to domestic abuse. The consultation closed on 31 May. Over 3,200 responses to the consultation were received. The responses to the consultation are being considered and a draft Bill will be published later this session.</p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins",,"2018-06-19T11:05:00.8Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921979/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921979/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921979/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-06-11","Domestic Abuse","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the timetable is for his Department to respond to it's consultation on the draft Domestic Violence and Abuse Bill; and what the timetable is for further steps to be taken in relation to that Bill.","false","Biography information for Julie Elliott","Sunderland Central","Julie Elliott","152171"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921980","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-06-18","<p>Local authorities and housing associations must remove dangerous Aluminium Composite Material (ACM) cladding quickly. We want to get funding to local authorities and housing associations as soon as possible. We will announce more details shortly about how local authorities and housing associations can apply for funding, including conditions attached to the grant.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2018-06-18T14:34:31.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921980/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921980/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921980/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-06-11","Social Rented Housing: Fire Prevention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what the timetable is for (a) local authorities and (b) housing associations to access the funding for the removal and replacement of unsafe cladding announced by the Government on 16 May 2018.","false","Biography information for Helen Hayes","Dulwich and West Norwood","Helen Hayes","152253"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921981","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-06-18","<p>The Government will fully fund the removal and replacement of dangerous Aluminium Composite Material (ACM) cladding, of the types which have failed large scale tests, on residential buildings over 18 metres owned by social landlords, with costs estimated at £400 million.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2018-06-18T14:37:23.1Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921981/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921981/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921981/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-06-11","Social Rented Housing: Fire Prevention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, pursuant to his oral contribution of 16 May 2018, Official Report, column 317, for the removal and replacement of what types of unsafe cladding he plans to allocate funding to local authorities and housing associations.","false","Biography information for Helen Hayes","Dulwich and West Norwood","Helen Hayes","152254"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921982","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-06-18","<p>Yes, the Government will fully fund the removal and replacement of dangerous Aluminium Composite Material (ACM) cladding on residential buildings over 18 metres owned by social landlords, regardless of whether or not the work has been completed.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2018-06-18T14:36:13.053Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921982/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921982/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921982/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-06-11","Social Rented Housing: Fire Prevention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, whether (a) local authorities and (b) housing associations will be able to apply retrospectively for funding for works already carried out to remove unsafe cladding from tower blocks.","false","Biography information for Helen Hayes","Dulwich and West Norwood","Helen Hayes","152255"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921983","Home Office","false","2018-06-14","<p>On 8 March we launched a 12 week public consultation on proposals for a landmark domestic abuse Bill and a supporting package of practical action to transform the response to domestic abuse. The consultation closed on 31 May. Over 3,200 responses to the consultation were received. The responses to the consultation are being considered and a draft Bill will be published later this session.</p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins",,"2018-06-14T16:25:28.777Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921983/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921983/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921983/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-06-11","Domestic Abuse","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the timetable is for his Department to respond to it's consultation on the draft Domestic Violence and Abuse Bill; and what the timetable is for further steps to be taken in relation to that Bill.","false","Biography information for Anna McMorrin","Cardiff North","Anna McMorrin","152271"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921984","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-06-19","<p>NHS Digital is responsible for implementing this recommendation. It continues to work to improve processes required to gain research approvals and to make the data applicant process more efficient. NHS Digital is working with others in the sector to ensure consistent understanding of the laws, policy and guidance around the use of health data in research.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2018-06-19T13:22:24.12Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921984/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921984/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921984/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-06-11","Life Sciences: Databases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps he has taken to streamline the (a) ethical and (b) legal approval processes for national datasets recommended in the Life Sciences Industrial Strategy; and which body is responsible for the implementation of that recommendation.","false","Biography information for Helen Hayes","Dulwich and West Norwood","Helen Hayes","152256"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921985","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-06-19","<p>​The UK has a continuing dialogue with the Government of Bahrain in which we raise individual cases. Our Embassy in Bahrain has monitored this specific case and will attend the next hearing. The UK encourages those with concerns about treatment in detention to report these to the relevant human rights oversight bodies. We urge these bodies to carry out swift and thorough investigations. The UK continues to encourage the Government of Bahrain to deliver on its international and domestic human rights commitments.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-06-19T14:53:00.513Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921985/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921985/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921985/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-06-11","Najah al-Sheikh","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations he has made to his Bahraini counterpart on allegations of torture by Bahraini activist Najah Al Sheikh; and whether UK representatives will attend her next hearing on 25 June.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","152048"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921986","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-06-19","<p>​I refer the honourable gentleman to the answer I gave to question 139036. We encourage those with concerns about treatment in detention to report these to the appropriate oversight body. We urge these oversight bodies to carry out swift and thorough investigations into any such claims. We understand that the National Institution for Human Rights is aware of this case and is monitoring the situation, and that the Ombudsman of the Ministry of the Interior is also investigating the claims and has been in touch with Ms Mansoor. We have raised the case with the Government of Bahrain at a senior level and continue to monitor the situation.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-06-19T14:54:57.513Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921986/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921986/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921986/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-06-11","Hajer Mansoor Hassan","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent representations he has made to his Bahraini counterpart on detention conditions and access to medical care for detainee Hajer Mansoor.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","152049"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921987","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-06-19","<p>​The UK has concerns about the revocation of nationality when it renders a person stateless. We have raised this at a senior level with the Government of Bahrain and will continue to do so.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-06-19T14:56:24.5Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921987/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921987/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921987/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-06-11","Bahrain: Politics and Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent representations he has made to his Bahraini counterpart on the outcome of the trial which revoked the citizenship of 115 people and left some stateless.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","152050"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921988","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-06-14","<p>The Ministry of Justice, through Government Facility Services Limited (GFSL), has met with a wide range of suppliers as part of transitioning the HMPPS Facilities Management contracts. The MoJ took the decision early to manage suppliers to mitigate exposure and protect the supply chain, and have looked to support these suppliers wherever possible and have been in regular contact with the supply chain. Given the number of suppliers concerned, the Department doesn’t keep a record of which former Carillion suppliers it has met with. The MoJ is committed to working with SME’s and is already close to achieving the Government 2020 target. <br> <br> To expedite the creation of GFSL a decision was taken to mobilise the MOJ infrastructure to ensure that at the point of Carillion entering Provisional Liquidation a process was in place to take on this work directly, mitigate continued exposure to the supply chain and ensure continuity of service. GFSL are currently working with the MOJ to review the interim process and move towards a revised operating model. The proposed approach will continue to see a reliance on the private sector and in particular SME providers.</p><p><br> The Ministry of Justice is aware of a limited number of redundancies made by SMEs, however it is not able to determine if these directly relate to goods or services provided by Carillion to the Department</p><p><br> Government Facility Services Limited (GFSL) is currently being supported by the Ministry of Justice in respect of contracts with the supply chain. Following Carillion entering Provisional Liquidation the majority of purchasing was undertaken via the MoJ to ensure stable supply chain arrangements remained in place. This will move across to GFSL later this year. GFSL intends to pay its suppliers promptly and will take steps to ensure compliance with the Prompt Payment Code.</p><p>The performance statistics of the MoJ in respect of paying invoices can be found via: https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/ministry-of-justice/about/procurement#our-payment-performance</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart","152165 ; 152166 ; 152167 ; 152168","2018-06-14T16:32:56.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921988/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921988/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/921988/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-06-11","Ministry of Justice: Carillion","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many SMEs who were previously sub-contracted by Carillion to provide goods and services on behalf of his Department and its agencies he has met with since that company was liquidated.","false","Biography information for Catherine McKinnell","Newcastle upon Tyne North","Catherine McKinnell","152164"
