"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/919276","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-06-15","<p>We assess recent attacks on shipping in the Bab al Mandeb to be linked with the conflict in Yemen rather than attempted piracy. The UK plays an active role in protecting shipping in the Bab al-Mandeb through: our support for the Combined Maritime Forces, a multinational naval partnership with a UK Deputy Commander; the presence in the region of a Royal Navy Mine Counter Measures Squadron; and the Royal Navy’s United Kingdom Maritime Trade Operations office in Dubai, which is the primary point of contact for merchant vessels in case of a security incident in the region. We also continue to play a major role in international efforts to combat piracy in the wider West Indian Ocean, and provide the Operational HQ for the EU’s counter-piracy mission, Operation Atalanta.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-06-15T13:10:59.367Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/919276/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/919276/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/919276/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-06-07","Yemen: Piracy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps the Government is taking to help tackle piracy in the Bab Al Mandeb Strait.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","151062"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/919277","Department for International Development","false","2018-06-12","<p>The UN assess that an attack on Hodeidah could displace up to 350,000 people and leave hundreds of thousands of Yemenis without access to basic goods, water or healthcare. 17.8 million people in Yemen already lack reliable access to food – 8.4 million of which face extreme food shortages. UN estimates suggest any long closure of Hodeidah port is likely to put over 3 million more people at risk of starvation.</p><p> </p><p>The UK government has been clear in expressing its concerns to Saudi Arabia and the United Arab Emirates about any attack on Hodeidah. We urge all parties to the conflict to exercise restraint and to continue to facilitate access for essential commercial and humanitarian imports of food, fuel and medical supplies into the country, including through Hodeidah port.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-06-12T13:58:04.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/919277/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/919277/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/919277/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-06-07","Yemen: Ports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, whether her Department has made an assessment of the humanitarian effect on the local population of a military assault on Hodeida port in Yemen by the Saudi-led coalition.","false","Biography information for Gill Furniss","Sheffield, Brightside and Hillsborough","Gill Furniss","151234"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/919278","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-06-12","<p>The British Government has been clear in expressing its concerns about any attack on Hodeidah. We call upon all sides to show restraint, urgently de-escalate and engage in good faith in the political process. It is essential that the UN Special Envoy is given the time and space needed to facilitate a negotiated solution that avoids conflict in the city. We continue to be unequivocal in stressing that only a political solution can bring long-term stability to Yemen – there is no military solution.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-06-12T15:06:14.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/919278/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/919278/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/919278/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-06-07","Yemen: Ports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment his Department has made on the effect of a military assault on Hodeida port in Yemen by the Saudi-led coalition on the prospects of a UN-negotiated peace plan.","false","Biography information for Gill Furniss","Sheffield, Brightside and Hillsborough","Gill Furniss","151235"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/919279","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-06-12","<p>Export licences for all countries, including Saudi Arabia and the United Arab Emirates, are assessed on a case-by-case basis against the Consolidated EU &amp; National Arms Export Licensing Criteria. We keep our assessments under careful and continual review, in light of events. The Criteria state, among other things, that the Government will not grant a licence where there is a clear risk that the items might be used in the commission of a serious violation of international humanitarian law.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-06-12T15:09:11.373Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/919279/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/919279/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/919279/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-06-07","Gulf States: Arms Trade","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if he will make it his policy to stop arms sales to (a) Saudi Arabia and (b) United Arab Emirates in the event that the Saudi-led coalition initiates a military attack on Hodeida in Yemen.","false","Biography information for Gill Furniss","Sheffield, Brightside and Hillsborough","Gill Furniss","151236"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/919280","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-06-12","<p>Information about waiting times for Social Security and Child Support appeals (covering the period in question) is published on gov.uk and can be viewed using the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/tribunals-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/tribunals-statistics</a></p><p> </p><p> </p>","South East Cambridgeshire","Lucy Frazer",,"2018-06-12T13:16:00.253Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/919280/answer","Biography information for Lucy Frazer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/919280/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/919280/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-06-07","Social Security Benefits: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what is the average waiting time was for a social security tribunal hearing for each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","151140"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/919281","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-06-12","<p>We collect figures on the Department’s decision making in order to manage the throughput of work and level of service provided. That information does include the number of decisions made, mandatory reconsiderations and appeals. However, we don't collate information on individual decision makers for the purpose of performance management.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2018-06-12T17:04:46.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/919281/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/919281/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/919281/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-06-07","Department for Work and Pensions: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what figures her Department collects on her Department's decision makers for the purposes of performance management; and whether those figures include the number of (a) decisions made, (b) mandatory reconsiderations and (c) decisions overturned on appeal.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","151141"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/919282","Home Office","false","2018-06-13","<p>The latest available data are published in the Police recorded crime open data tables, available here:<a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/police-recorded-crime-open-data-tables" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/police-recorded-crime-open-data-tables</a></p><p>The Home Office does not hold information on the number of people that have been prosecuted and convicted. This information should be requested from the Ministry of Justice.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p /><p /><p> </p><p />","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2018-06-13T15:22:24.06Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/919282/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/919282/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/919282/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-06-07","Drugs: Crime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many people have been (a) charged, (b) prosecuted and (c) convicted for a suspected (i) drug trafficking or (ii) drug supply offence in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Sir Edward Davey","Kingston and Surbiton","Sir Edward Davey","151022"
